**What this is.** The GWAS model Chen 2019 actually used for **Fig 4C** — a linear
**mixed model** with population structure (Q) and kinship (K) — run in TASSEL5 on the
**authentic 118,838-SNP GWAS panel** (Qiuyue Chen's Drive release, lifted to v5,
118,514 markers), and contrasted with the fixed-effect **OLS** scan
([`teonam-stam-ols-gwas-118k`](teonam-stam-ols-gwas-118k.html)).

Crucially, this panel is only **~2.7% missing** (Chen's MR &lt; 0.2 GWAS SNPs), so the
MLM runs **directly on it — no densification / step-interpolation**. That preserves
the natural per-SNP **scatter** of a real GWAS Manhattan. This is the faithful Fig-4C
reproduction that the interpolated 51K MLM notebook
([`teonam-stam-mlm-gwas-interpolated`](teonam-stam-mlm-gwas-interpolated.html)) could
not be: there, the 73%-missing 51K **map** panel had to be step-interpolated to a
complete matrix, which made genotypes block-constant → a **terraced/plateau** Manhattan
and a spurious **over-correction** (kinship absorbing each QTL's own-chromosome signal).
Here, with the real GWAS panel, neither artifact applies. Compute lives in
`scripts/teonam_mlm118k.R`; this notebook loads, documents, and plots.

```{r setup}
library(here)
library(data.table)
library(ggplot2)
theme_set(theme_bw(base_size = 13))
LOD &lt;- 5 # Chen 2019 significance line: P &lt; 1e-5

# genomic inflation factor: median(chi^2_obs) / median(chi^2_null)
lambda_gc &lt;- function(p) {
  p &lt;- p[is.finite(p) & p &gt; 0 & p &lt;= 1]
  round(median(qchisq(p, df = 1, lower.tail = FALSE)) / qchisq(0.5, df = 1), 3)
}

The scan

scan1 &lt;- function(i) {
  g &lt;- dos[i, ] # dosage across lines, NA where untyped
  ok &lt;- !is.na(g) & !is.na(y)
  n &lt;- sum(ok)
  if (n &lt; 20) {
    return(c(NA_real_, n))
  }
  gg &lt;- as.numeric(g[ok])
  if (stats::sd(gg) == 0) {
    return(c(NA_real_, n))
  }
  yy &lt;- y[ok]
  ff &lt;- droplevels(fam[ok])
  Xr &lt;- if (nlevels(ff) &gt; 1) model.matrix(~ff) else matrix(1, n, 1)
  RSS0 &lt;- sum(lm.fit(Xr, yy)$residuals^2)
  fit &lt;- lm.fit(cbind(Xr, gg), yy)
  RSS1 &lt;- sum(fit$residuals^2)
  df2 &lt;- n - fit$rank
  if (df2 &lt;= 0 || RSS1 &lt;= 0) {
    return(c(NA_real_, n))
  }
  c(pf(((RSS0 - RSS1) / 1) / (RSS1 / df2), 1, df2, lower.tail = FALSE), n)
}
out &lt;- mclapply(mk_idx, scan1, mc.cores = THREADS)
P &lt;- vapply(out, `[`, numeric(1), 1)
N &lt;- vapply(out, `[`, numeric(1), 2)

scan &lt;- data.table(
  SNP = mk, CHR = as.integer(chr_by[mk]),
  BP = as.integer(pos_by[mk]), P = P,
  n = as.integer(N)
)[order(CHR, BP)]
fwrite(scan, here("data/teonam/stam_gwas_scan_118k.csv")) # canonical output

Notes

This notebook is the canonical, tracked source for stam_gwas_scan_118k.csv; it ports scripts/teonam_stam_gwas118k.R verbatim (same OLS model as the 51K family-imputed notebook).
The marker set is the authentic Chen 2019 GWAS panel (118,838 SNPs → 118,514 lifted to v5), not the 51K map panel. Same model, different markers → the two OLS notebooks are directly comparable.
Model is OLS (fixed effects), no kinship term — the peak-height / \(\lambda_{GC}\) comparison against Chen’s Q + K mixed model is deferred to a dedicated inflation notebook (the 118K MLM analog is not yet built).





